The row polynomials P(n,x) = (a. + x)^n, umbrally evaluated with (a.)^n = a_n = aerated A001147, are an Appell sequence with dP(n,x)/dx = n * P(n-1,x). The umbral compositional inverses (cf. A001147) of these polynomials are given by the same polynomials signed, A066325. - _Tom Copeland_, Nov 15 2014

The odd rows are (2x^2)^n x n! L(n,-1/(2x^2),1/2), and the even, (2x^2)^n n! L(n,-1/(2x^2),-1/2) in sequence with n= 0,1,2,... and L(n,x,a) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n+a,k+a) (-x)^k/k!, the associated Laguerre polynomial of order a. The odd rows are related to A130757, and the even to A176230 and A176231. Other versions of this entry are A122848, A049403, A096713 and A104556, and reversed A100861, A144299, A111924. With each non-vanishing diagonal divided by its initial element A001147(n), this array becomes reversed, aerated A034839.

Create four shift and stretch matrices S1,S2,S3, and S4 with all elements zero except S1(2n,n) = 1 for n >= 1, S2(n,2n) = 1 for n >= 0, S3(2n+1,n) = 1 for n >= 1, and S4(n,2n+1) = 1 for n >= 0. Then this entry's lower triangular matrix is T = Id + S1 * (A176230-Id) * S2 + S3 * (unsigned A130757-Id) * S4 with Id the identity matrix. The sandwiched matrices have infinitesimal generators with the nonvanishing subdiagonals A000384(n>0) and A014105(n>0).

As an Appell sequence, the lowering and raising operators are L = D and R = x + dlog(exp(D^2/2))/dD = x + D, where D = d/dx, L h(n,x) = n h(n-1,x), and R h(n,x) = h(n+1,x), so R^n 1 = h(n,x). The fundamental moment sequence has the e.g.f. e^(t^2/2) with coefficients a(n) = aerated A001147, i.e., h(n,x) = (a. + x)^n, as noted above. The raising operator R as a matrix acting on o.g.f.s (formal power series) is the transpose of the production matrix P below, i.e., (1,x,x^2,...)(P^T)^n (1,0,0,...)^T = h(n,x).
For characterization as a Riordan array and associations to combinatorial structures, see the Barry link and the Yang and Qiao reference. For relations to projective modules, see the Sazdanovic link.

From the Appell formalism, e^(D^2/2) x^n = h_n(x), the n-th row polynomial listed below, and e^(-D^2/2) x^n = u_n(x), the n-th row polynomial of A066325. Then R = e^(D^2/2) * x * e^(-D^2/2) is another representation of the raising operator, implied by the umbral compositional inverse relation h_n(u.(x)) = x^n. - _Tom Copeland_, Oct 02 2016
h_n(x) = p_n(x-1), where p_n(x) are the polynomials of A111062, related to the telephone numbers A000085. - _Tom Copeland_, Jun 26 2018
In the power basis x^n, the matrix infinitesimal generator M = A132440^2/2, when acting on a row vector for an o.g.f., is the matrix representation for the differential operator D^2/2.
e^{M} gives the coefficients of the Hermite polynomials of this entry.

The only nonvanishing subdiagonal of M, the second subdiagonal (1,3,6,10,...), gives, aside from the initial 0, the triangular numbers A000217, the number of edges of the n-dimensional simplices with (n+1) vertices. The perfect matchings of these simplices are the aerated odd double factorials A001147 noted above, the moments for the Hermite polynomials.
The polynomials are also generated from A036040 with x[1] = x, x[2] = 1, and the other indeterminates equal to zero. (End)

A099361.name: A variation on the sieve of Eratosthenes (A000040): Start with the primes; the first term is 2, which is a(1) and we cross off every second prime starting with 2; the next prime not crossed off is 3, which is a(2) and we cross off every third prime starting with 3; the next prime not crossed off is 7, which is a(3) and we cross off every 7th prime starting with 7; and so on.

A099362.name: Number of times the n-th prime is crossed off in the sieve of A099361.

A099363.name: An inverse Chebyshev transform of 1-x.

a(n) = (-1)^n A208355(n) = (-1)^n A000108([(n+1)/2]): Repeated Catalan numbers with alternating sign. - _M. F. Hasler_, Aug 25 2012

A099366.name: Squares of A005668(n) (generalized Fibonacci).
formula: a(n) = (T(n, 19) - (-1)^n)/20 with the Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind: T(n, 19) = A078986(n).

A099367.name: Squares of A054413(n-1), n>=1,(generalized Fibonacci).
formula: a(n)= 2*(T(n, 51/2)-(-1)^n)/53 with twice the Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind: 2*T(n, 51/2)=A099368(n).

A099368.name: Twice Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind, T(n,x), evaluated at x=51/2.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 51) - S(n-2, 51) = 2*T(n, 51/2) with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), S(-1, x) := 0, S(-2, x) := -1. S(n, 51)=A097836(n). U-, resp. T-, are Chebyshev polynomials of the second, resp. first, case. See A049310 and A053120.
a(n)= ap^n + am^n, with ap:=(51 + 7*sqrt(53))/2 and am:=(51 - 7*sqrt(53))/2.

A099369.name: Squares of A041025(n-1), n>=1, (generalized Fibonacci).
formula: a(n)= (T(n, 33)-(-1)^n)/34 with the Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind: T(n, 33)=A099370(n).

A099370.name: Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind, T(n,x), evaluated at x=33.
formula: a(n) = T(n, 33) = (S(n, 66)-S(n-2, 66))/2 = S(n, 66)-33*S(n-1, 66) with T(n, x), resp. S(n, x), Chebyshev polynomials of the first, resp.second, kind. See A053120 and A049310. S(n, 66)=A097316(n).

A099371.name: Expansion of g.f.: x/(1 - 9*x - x^2).
formula: a(n) = (-i)^(n-1)*S(n-1, 9*i) with S(n, x) Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind (see A049310) and i^2=-1.
a(n) = (ap^n - am^p)/(ap-am) with ap:= (9+sqrt(85))/2 and am:= (9-sqrt(85))/2=-1/ap (Binet form).
a(n) = F(n, 9), the n-th Fibonacci polynomial evaluated at x=9. - _T. D. Noe_, Jan 19 2006
a(n) = ((9+sqrt(85))^n - (9-sqrt(85))^n)/(2^n*sqrt(85)). Offset 1. a(3)=82. - Al Hakanson (hawkuu(AT)gmail.com), Jan 12 2009
a(n) = [1,0] (M^n) [0,1]^T where M is the matrix [9,1; 1,0]. - _Robert Israel_, Feb 01 2015

A099372.name: Squares of A099371(n) (generalized Fibonacci).
formula: a(n)= 2*(T(n, 83/2)-(-1)^n)/85 with twice the Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind: 2*T(n, 83/2)=A099373(n).

A099373.name: Twice Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind, T(n,x), evaluated at 83/2.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 83) - S(n-2, 83) = 2*T(n, 83/2) with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), S(-1, x) := 0, S(-2, x) := -1. S(n, 83)= A097839(n). U-, resp. T-, are Chebyshev polynomials of the second, resp. first, case. See A049310 and A053120.
a(n) = ap^n + am^n, with ap := (83+9*sqrt(85))/2 and am := (83-9*sqrt(85))/2.

A099374.name: Squares of A041041(n-1), n>=1 (generalized Fibonacci).
formula: a(n)= (T(n, 51)-(-1)^n)/52 with the Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind: T(n, 51)=(n).

formula: a(n)=2*A004736(n)-1; a(n)=2*((t*t+3*t+4)/2-n)-1, where t=floor((-1+sqrt(8*n-7))/2). - _Boris Putievskiy_, Feb 08 2013

Euler transform of length 10 sequence [1, 0, 0, -1, -1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1]. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 18 2006
a(n) = -a(n-5) = -a(-2-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 18 2006
0 = (a(n) - a(n+1)) * (a(n) - a(n+1) + a(n+2)) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 07 2014

a(n+1) = 1 - sum(A101950(n-k+2, k+2), k=0..floor(n/2)) - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Aug 06 2013

A099508.name: A transform of the Jacobsthal numbers.

A099510.name: Triangle, read by rows, of trinomial coefficients arranged so that there are n+1 terms in row n by setting T(n,k) equal to the coefficient of z^k in (1 + 2*z + z^2)^(n-[k/2]), for n>=k>=0, where [k/2] is the integer floor of k/2.

A099511.name: Row sums of triangle A099510, so that a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} coefficient of z^k in (1 + 2*z + z^2)^(n-[k/2]), where [k/2] is the integer floor of k/2.

A099512.name: Triangle, read by rows, of trinomial coefficients arranged so that there are n+1 terms in row n by setting T(n,k) equal to the coefficient of z^k in (1 + 3*z + z^2)^(n-[k/2]), for n>=k>=0, where [k/2] is the integer floor of k/2.

A099513.name: Row sums of triangle A099512, so that a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} coefficient of z^k in (1 + 3*z + z^2)^(n-[k/2]), where [k/2] is the integer floor of k/2.

A099514.name: Triangle, read by rows, of trinomial coefficients arranged so that there are n+1 terms in row n by setting T(n,k) equal to the coefficient of z^k in (1 + z + 2*z^2)^(n-[k/2]), for n>=k>=0, where [k/2] is the integer floor of k/2.

A099515.name: Row sums of triangle A099514, so that a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} coefficient of z^k in (1 + z + 2*z^2)^(n-[k/2]), where [k/2] is the integer floor of k/2.

A099516.name: A transform of the Pell numbers.

A099519.name: Positions in A099506 of the values in the RECORDS transform of that sequence (A099518).

A099520.name: a(1)=1; for n>1, a(n)=smallest integer m>0 not yet appearing in sequence such that m+a(n-1) is a multiple of n-1.

A099523.name: Positions in sequence A099520 at which its records (as given in A099522) appear.

A099527.name: Triangle, read by rows, of trinomial coefficients arranged so that there are n+1 terms in row n by setting T(n,k) equal to the coefficient of z^k in (2 + 3*z + z^2)^(n-[k/2]), for n>=k>=0, where [k/2] is the integer floor of k/2.

A099528.name: Row sums of triangle A099527, so that a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} coefficient of z^k in (2 + 3*z + z^2)^(n-[k/2]), where [k/2] is the integer floor of k/2.

A099532.name: Lesser of a,b where n^2 = a^3 + b^3; a,b > 0 and gcd(a,b)=1. The greater of a,b is the corresponding term in A099533 and n, which is used to order this sequence, is the corresponding term in A099426.

A099533.name: Greater of a,b where n^2 = a^3 + b^3; a,b>0 and gcd(a,b)=1. The lesser of a,b is the corresponding term in A099532 and n, which is used to order this sequence, is the corresponding term in A099426.

A099534.name: a(n)=Sum of the first n decimal places of e.

A099535.name: Sum of the first n decimal places of log(2).

A099536.name: Sum of the first n digits of Zeta(3) (Apery's constant), including the initial 1.

A099537.name: Sum of the first n decimal places of zeta(3) (Apery's constant). This does not include the initial "1." of zeta(3).

A099538.name: Sum of the first n digits of sqrt(2), including the initial "1".

A099539.name: Sum of the first n decimal places of sqrt(2).

A099540.name: Sum of the first n digits of log(Pi)=1.14472988584940017...

A099541.name: Sum of the first n decimal places of log(Pi).

A099543.name: Sums of the prime factors of the Rhonda numbers to base 10 (sequence A099542). The terms in this sequence are equal to (Product of digits of terms of A099542)/10, which is simply the definition of Rhonda numbers to base 10.

A099551.name: Odd part of n modulo 10. Final digit of A000265(n).
formula: G.f. g(x) satisfies: g(x) = g(x^2) + (x + 3*x^3 + 5*x^5 + 7*x^7 + 9*x^9)/(1-x^10). - _Robert Israel_, Aug 10 2018

A099552.name: a(n) is the smallest positive integer such that the concatenation of the first n terms is divisible by n.

A099553.name: Number of rooted 2-connected loopless 4-regular planar maps with n inner faces.
formula: G.f.: x*(A(x) - 1) where A(x) satisfies A(x) = G(x*A(x)^2) and (G(x) + 2*x - 1)/x is the g.f. of A000139. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Apr 06 2021

A099554.name: Decimal expansion of the constant x that satisfies x = exp(1/sqrt(x)).

A099555.name: Triangle, read by rows, where T(n,k) = (n-[k/2])^k and [k/2] is the integer floor of k/2, for 2n>=k>=0.

A099556.name: Row sums of triangle A099555, so that a(n) = Sum_{k=0..2n} (n-[k/2])^k where [k/2] is the integer floor of k/2.

A099557.name: Slanted Pascal's triangle, read by rows, such that T(n,k) = binomial(n-[k/2],k) for [n*2/3]>=k>=0, where [x]=floor(x).

A099558.name: Antidiagonal sums of the triangle A099557.

A099559.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/5)} C(n-4k,k+1).
formula: Partial sums of A003520 (with leading zero).

A099563.name: a(0) = 0; for n > 0, a(n) = final nonzero number in the sequence n, f(n,2), f(f(n,2),3), f(f(f(n,2),3),4),..., where f(n,d) = floor(n/d); the most significant digit in the factorial base representation of n.
formula: a(0) = 0; for n >= 1, if A265333(n) = 1 [when n is one of the terms of A265334], a(n) = 1, otherwise 1 + a(A257684(n)).
a(A001563(n)) = n. [Sequence works as a left inverse for A001563.]

A099564.name: a(0) = 0; for n > 0, a(n) = final nonzero number in the sequence n, f(n,2), f(f(n,2),3), f(f(f(n,2),3),4),..., where f(n,d)=Floor(n/F(d+1)), with F denoting the Fibonacci numbers (A000045).

A099567.name: Riordan array (1/(1-x-x^3),1/(1-x)).
formula: Number triangle T(n, k)=sum{j=0..n, binomial(n-2j, k+j)}; Columns have g.f. (1/(1-x-x^3))(x/(1-x))^k.
T(n,0)=A000930(n), T(n,n)=1, T(n,k)=T(n-1,k-1)+T(n-1,k) for 0<k<n. - _Philippe Deléham_, Dec 29 2013

exp(x) * e.g.f. for row n = e.g.f. for diagonal n. For example, for n = 3 we have exp(x)*(2 + 3*x + 3*x^2/2! + x^3/3!) = 2 + 5*x + 11*x^2/2! + 21*x^3/3! + 36*x^4/4! + .... The same property holds more generally for Riordan arrays of the form ( f(x), x/(1 - x) ). - _Peter Bala_, Dec 21 2014

A099569.name: Riordan array ((1+x)^2-x^3)/(1+x)^3, 1/(1+x)).
formula: T(n,k) = (-1)^(n+k)*(C(n,n-k) + Sum_{i = 3..n} (i-2)*C(n-i,n-k-i)), where C(n,k) = n!/(k!*(n-k)!) for 0 <= k <= n, otherwise 0. - _Peter Bala_, Mar 21 2018

A099572.name: Sum C(n-k+4,k), k=0..floor(n/2).
formula: G.f.: 1/((1-x^2)^4*(1-x-x^2)); - corrected by R. J. Mathar, Feb 20 2011

A099573.name: Reverse of number triangle A054450.
formula: Number triangle T(n, k)=if(k<=n, sum{j=0..floor(k/2), binomial(n-j, j)}, 0).

Antidiagonals of the following array: the first row equals the Fibonacci numbers, (1, 1, 2, 3, 5,...), and the (n+1)-st row is obtained by the matrix-vector product A128174 * n-th row. - Gary W. Adamson, Jan 19 2011

A099583.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n-k, k-1)*2^(n-k-1)*(3/2)^(k-1).
formula: a(n) = A002452(n/2) if n even; a(n) = 2*A006100((n+1)/2) if n odd. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jun 06 2010
a(0)=0, a(1)=0; a(2)=1; a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 3*a(n-2) if n is odd; a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 3*a(n-2) + 3^m (m=1,2,3...) if n is even. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Jun 26 2010

A099584.name: Exponent of 3 in factorization of prime(n) - 1.

A099586.name: Constant term in (1+x)^n mod (1+x^4).
formula: a(n) = round((2+sqrt(2))^(n/2)*cos(Pi*(n)/8)/2), where round(x) is the integer nearest to x.

A099587.name: a(n) = coefficient of x in (1+x)^n mod (1+x^4).
formula: a(n) = round((2+sqrt(2))^(n/2)*cos(Pi*(n-2)/8)/2), where round(x) is the integer nearest to x.

A099588.name: Coefficient of x^2 in (1+x)^n mod 1+x^4.
formula: a(n) = round((2+sqrt(2))^(n/2)*cos(Pi*(n-4)/8)/2), where round(x) is the integer nearest to x;

A099589.name: Expansion of x^3 / (1 - 4x + 6x^2 - 4x^3 + 2x^4).
formula: G.f.: x^3/((1-x)^4 + x^4), the binomial transform of x^3/(1+x^4). - _Paul Barry_, Apr 01 2005
a(n) = round((2+sqrt(2))^(n/2)*cos(Pi*(n-6)/8)/2), where round(x) is the integer nearest to x.

A099590.name: 2^(n-1) times coefficient of x in (1+x)^n mod U(n,x), U the Chebyshev polynomials.

A099591.name: Numbers that are the sum of no fewer than 17 biquadrates (4th powers).

A099592.name: Minimum index i of certain Lucas (or Lehmer) sequences such that every element with index >= i has a primitive divisor.

A099593.name: Sum of the number of e-divisors of all numbers from 2 up to n.

A099594.name: Array read by antidiagonals: poly-Bernoulli numbers B(-k,n).
formula: pB(k, n) = (-1)^n * Sum[i=0..n, (-1)^i * i! * Stirling2(n, i) / (i+1)^k ].
T(n, k) = Sum_{j=0..n} (j+1)^k*Sum_{i=0..j} (-1)^(n+j-i)*C(j, i)*(j-i)^n. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Nov 04 2004
n-th row of the array = row sums of n-th power of triangle A210381. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Mar 21 2012

A099595.name: Molien series for complete weight enumerators of Euclidean self-dual doubly-even codes over the Galois ring GR(4,2) that contain the all-ones vector.

A099596.name: Primes p such that the denominator of the poly-Bernoulli number B(2,n) equals 8p.

A099597.name: Array T(k,n) read by antidiagonals: expansion of exp(x+y)/(1-xy).
formula: T(n,k) = sum {i=0..min(n,k)} C(n,i)*C(k,i)*i!^2. The LDU factorization of this square array is P * D * transpose(P), where P is Pascal's triangle A007318 and D = diag(0!^2, 1!^2, 2!^2, ... ). Compare with A088699. - _Peter Bala_, Nov 06 2007
Recurrence equation: T(n,k) = n*k*T(n-1,k-1) + 1 with boundary conditions T(n,0) = T(0,n ) = 1.
Main subdiagonal and main superdiagonal [1, 3, 19, 229, ...] is A228229. - _Peter Bala_, Aug 19 2013

A099598.name: Antidiagonal sums of array A099597.
formula: a(n)=sum{k=0..n, C(n,k)*(floor(k/2)!)^2}; a(n)=sum{k=0..n, sum{j=0..n-k, C(n-k,j)C(k,j)j!^2}}; - _Paul Barry_, May 26 2007

A099599.name: Triangle T read by rows: coefficients of polynomials generating array A099597.
formula: The row polynomials satisfy the second order recurrence equation R(n,x) = (n*x+1)*R(n-1,x-1) - (n-1)*(x-1)*R(n-2,x-2), with the initial conditions R(0,x) = 1 and R(1,x) = 1+x. - _Peter Bala_, Aug 19 2013

A099600.name: Inventory application: Numerator of the probability (rounded to the nearest trillionth: (10^-12)-th) of at least one shortage per month when n customers each request one item on one independently-chosen random day of a 30-day month, but when only exactly one such item is available per day.
formula: a(n) = round(10^12 * (1. - 30!/ ((30-n)! * 30^n) )) for 0 <= n <= 30. This corresponds, with d=30, to P_2(n, d) at the MathWorld Birthday Problem link. Clearly the probability is 1 and so a(n) = 10^12 here for all n > 30.

A099601.name: Quotient of de Bruijn sums S(4,n)/S(2,n).
formula: a(n) = [x^n]  1/(1 - x)*( Legendre_P(m*n,(1 + x)/(1 - x)) ) at m = 2. At m = 1 we get the Apéry numbers A005258. - _Peter Bala_, Dec 23 2020

A099602.name: Triangle, read by rows, such that row n equals the inverse binomial transform of column n of the triangle of trinomial coefficients (A027907), omitting leading zeros.

A099603.name: Row sums of triangle A099602, in which row n equals the inverse binomial transform of column n of the triangle of trinomial coefficients (A027907).

A099604.name: Antidiagonal sums of triangle A099602, in which row n equals the inverse binomial transform of column n of the triangle of trinomial coefficients (A027907).

A099605.name: Triangle, read by rows, such that row n equals the inverse binomial transform of column n of the triangle A034870 of coefficients in successive powers of the trinomial (1+2*x+x^2), omitting leading zeros.

A099606.name: Row sums of triangle A099605, in which row n equals the inverse Binomial transform of column n of the triangle A034870 of even-indexed rows of Pascal's triangle.

A099607.name: Antidiagonal sums of triangle A099605, in which row n equals the inverse binomial transform of column n of the triangle A034870 of even-indexed rows of Pascal's triangle.

A099608.name: Table of crystal ball sequences for A_n lattices read by antidiagonals.

A099609.name: Naive list of twin primes (A077800 prefixed by 2, 3).

A099610.name: Smallest product of two distinct odd primes > n^2.

A099611.name: Greatest product of two distinct odd primes < n^2.

A099612.name: Numerators of the coefficients in the Taylor expansion of sec(x) + tan(x) around x=0.
formula: Let R(x) = (-1)^floor(x/2)*(4^(x+1)-2^(x+1))*((HurwitzZeta(-x,3/4) - HurwitzZeta(-x,1/4)) /(2^(-x)-2)-Zeta(-x))/Gamma(x+1) then a(n) = numerator(R(n)) and A099617(n) = denominator(R(n)) for n>=1. - _Peter Luschny_, Aug 25 2015

Let F(x,t) = exp(-I*t*x)*(1+(exp(exp(I*t))-1)/(exp(2*exp(I*t))+1)) and r(x) = ((cos(x*Pi/2)+sin(x*Pi/2))/Pi)*Integral_{t=0..2*Pi} F(x,t) then a(n) = numerator(r(n)) and A099617(n) = denominator(r(n)) for n>=1. - _Peter Luschny_, Aug 25 2015
a(n) = numerator(2^n*|Euler(n,1/2) - Euler(n,1)|/n!) for n>0 where Euler(n,x) are the Euler polynomials. (End)

Conjecture: For n >= 0, (-1)^n * a(n+1) is the numerator of the n-th term of the Taylor expansion of 1/(1 + sin(x)) around x = 0. [This is based on the fact that (sec(x) + tan(x))' = 1/(1 + sin(-x)). _Clark Kimberling_ in A279107 states my conjecture as a fact, but no proof or reference is given.] - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Oct 06 2019

A099613.name: Numerator of (1+1/n)^k - (1+k/n), 2<=k<=n, triangle read by rows.

A099614.name: Numerator of (1-1/n)^k - (1-k/n), 2<=k<=n, triangle read by rows.

A099615.name: Triangle read by rows, 2<=k<=n: T(n,k) = denominator of (1+1/n)^k-(1+k/n) and of (1-1/n)^k-(1-k/n).

A099616.name: Sum of the first n decimal places of Catalan's constant 0.9159655941772... (sequence A006752).

A099617.name: Denominators of the coefficients in the Taylor expansion of sec(x) + tan(x) around x=0.
formula: a(n) = denominator(2^n*|Euler(n,1/2) - Euler(n,1)|/n!) for n > 0 where Euler(n,x) are the Euler polynomials. (End)

Conjecture: For n >= 0, (-1)^n * a(n+1)/(n+1) is the denominator of the n-th term of the Taylor expansion of 1/(1 + sin(x)) around x = 0. [This is based on the fact that (sec(x) + tan(x))' = 1/(1 + sin(-x)). Cf. also the comments in A099612 and A279107.] - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Oct 06 2019

A099618.name: a(n) = 1 if the n-th prime == 1 mod 6, otherwise a(n) = 0.

A099627.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k)=2^n+2^k-1 with n>=k>=0.

A099628.name: Numbers m where m-th Catalan number A000108(m) = binomial(2m,m)/(m+1) is divisible by 2 but not by 4, i.e., where A048881(m) = 1.

A099629.name: Smallest and largest primes pairwise displayed with k digits from k=1,...,9 with distinct decimal digits.

A099630.name: Smallest and largest primes pairwise displayed with k digits from k=2,3,... with repeated decimal digits.

A099633.name: Numbers n such that (phi[n-2]+phi[n+2])/2 = phi[n]. 2-phi/balanced numbers. See also A066167.

A099640.name: Primes with subscripts described in A098213.
formula: a(n) = prime(A098213(n)). See explanations at A098213.

A099641.name: Number of solutions to x*frac[p(x)/x]<=Log[n] or A004648(n)<=Log[n].

A099642.name: a(n) is the smallest nonprime k such that tau(k + n) = tau(k) + n , where tau(n) is the number of divisors of n (A000005).

A099644.name: a[n]=Mod[q(n),PrimePi[q(n)]]=Mod[A001359(n), A000720[A001359(n))] where q(n) is the n-th lesser-twin-prime. A004648 restricted to lesser twins.

A099645.name: Number of iterations until n reaches a number in A039943 under "x goes to sum of squares of digits of x" map.

A099646.name: Function f(n) = 1 + Sum(digit^2 of n) is iterated and a(n) is the length of terminal cycle at initial value n.

A099647.name: Function f[n]=1+Sum[digit^2 of n] is iterated as in A099646. Values x for which A099646[x]=1 are listed here. These terms are analogous to happy-numbers [=A007770].

A099648.name: Largest term arising in complete-iteration-list (both transient and cycle) when f(x) = A003132(x) is iterated, i.e., if digit-squares of iterate added repeatedly until steady state (= either cycle or fixed point) is reached.

A099649.name: Solutions to A099648(k) > k, i.e., numbers such that the largest term in the iteration of the A003132() function strictly exceeds the initial value.

A099651.name: For each of the C(10,2) = 45 pairs of decimal digits, record the smallest prime containing only these digits (if one exists); sort.

A099652.name: Largest number arising if f[x]=1+A003132(x) function is iterated until steady state reached. Compare with A099648.

A099653.name: a(n) is the number of n-subsets (n=1,2,...,10) of the 10 decimal digits from which prime numbers can be constructed including all n distinct digits either with or without repetitions; a(n) <= binomial(10,n).
formula: a(n) = binomial(10,n) - binomial(6,n) - binomial(4,n); number of n-digit subsets minus "antiprime-digit subclasses" selected from {0, 2, 4, 5, 6, 8} and {0, 3, 6, 9} digit collections.

A099720.name: Molien series for complete weight enumerators of Euclidean self-dual codes over the Galois ring GR(4,2).

A099721.name: a(n) = n^2*(2*n+1).
formula: a(n) = ceiling(Sum_{i=n^2-(n-1)..n^2+(n-1)} s(i)), for n > 0 and integer i, where s(i) are the real solutions to x = i + sqrt(x), and the summation range excludes the integer solutions which occur where i is an oblong number (A002378). The fractional portion of the summation converges to 2/3 for large n. If s(i) is replaced with i, then the summation equals n^2*(2*n-1) = A015237. - _Richard R. Forberg_, Oct 15 2014

A099723.name: Nonprime-power sigma-perfect numbers: numbers n such that NPPSigma(n)=2*n, where, if n=Product p_i^r_i then NPPSigma(n)=Product{Sum p_i^s_i, s_i is not a prime number, 0<=s_i<=r_i}.

A099724.name: Decimal expansion of Sum_{k>0} (A000040(k+1)-A000040(k))/exp(k), where A000040(k) gives the k-th prime number and exp(k) is the natural exponential of k.

A099725.name: a(n) is the number of 1's in the period of the continued fraction of the square root of the n-th nonsquare integer.

A099726.name: Sum of remainders of the n-th prime mod k, for k = 1,2,3,...,n.
formula: a(n) = n*p - A024916(p) + Sum_{k=n+1..p} k*floor(p/k), where p = prime(n). - _Daniel Suteu_, Feb 02 2021

A099727.name: Concatenations of six consecutive primes forming a prime.

A099728.name: Least number B such that (A001359(n) - B^2)^2 - B is also the lesser of larger twin primes, or 0 if no such B exists.

A099730.name: Array read by antidiagonals. Rows contain odd numbers reaching same odd successor in Collatz function iteration.

A099731.name: This table shows the coefficients of sum formulas of n-th Fibonacci numbers (A000045). The k-th row (k>=1) contains T(i,k) for i=1 to k, where k=[2*n+1+(-1)^(n-1)]/4 and T(i,k) satisfies F(n)= Sum_{i=1..k} T(i,k) * n^(k-i)/(k-1)!.

A099732.name: Largest order of a solvable subgroup of the symmetric group S_n.
formula: a(n) <= 24^((n-1)/3). Equality holds iff n is a power of 4.

A099733.name: a(n) is the number of active cells after a solid n X n square has reached a static state or constant population, closed and infinite loop in Conway's Game of Life.

A099739.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} k!*mu(k), where mu() is the Moebius function.

A099740.name: a(n) = Sum{k|n} k!*mu(k), where mu() is the Moebius function.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} mu(k)*k!*x^k/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Feb 19 2017

A099741.name: a(1) = a(2) = 1; a(n) = a([n/2])+a([n/3]) (n >= 3).
formula: G.f. g(x) satisfies g(x) = x + (1+x)*g(x^2) + (1+x+x^2)*g(x^3). - _Robert Israel_, Mar 15 2018

A099742.name: Least number B such that (A001359(n)-B^2)^2+B is also the lesser of larger twin primes, or 0 if no such B exists.

A099743.name: Number of permutations with exactly 1 valley which avoid the pattern 1324.

A099744.name: Palindromes n such that 10n01 is a prime.

A099745.name: Number of permutations of [n] with exactly 2 valleys which avoid the permutation 1324.

A099748.name: Molien series for complete weight enumerators of Euclidean self-dual codes over the Galois ring GR(4,2) that contain the all-ones vector.

A099749.name: The number defined by the decimal string "a(2n) 1's followed by a(2n+1)" is prime.

A099750.name: Molien series for complete weight enumerators of doubly-even Euclidean self-dual codes over the Galois ring GR(4,2).

A099751.name: Number of ways to write n as differences of (-4)-gonal numbers. If pe(n):=1/2*n*((e-2)*n+(4-e)) is the n-th e-gonal number, then a(n) = |{(m,k) of Z X Z; pe(-1)(m+k)-pe(m-1)=n}| for e=-4. cf. A001227 for e in {3, -2, 6}, A048272 for e in {0, 1, 4, 8} and A035218 for e=-1.
formula: Multiplicative with a(2^e) = e-1 if e>0, a(3^e) = 1, a(p^e) = e+1 if p>3.

A099752.name: Molien series for symmetrized weight enumerators of doubly-even Euclidean self-dual codes over the Galois ring GR(4,2).

A099753.name: a(n) = (2*n+1)^(n+2).
formula: For r = 0, 1, 2, ..., the e.g.f. for the sequence (2*n+1)^(n+r) can be expressed in terms of the function U(z) = sum {n >= 0} (2*n+1)^(n-1)*z^(2*n+1)/(2^n*n!). See A214406 for details. In the present case, r = 2, and the resulting e.g.f. is 1/z*U(z)*(1 + 8*U(z)^2 + 3*U(z)^4)/(1 - U(z)^2)^5 taken at z = sqrt(2*x).

A099755.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,0)=1, T(n,n)=(2*n-1)!!+1, T(n,k) = 2*(n-k) * T(n-1,k-1) + 2*(k+1)*T(n-1,k).

A099756.name: For each single digit {0,1,...,9} record the smallest prime made up of copies of that digit (if there is one); repeat for all of the C(10,2) = 45 pairs of distinct decimal digits; then for all triples; etc.

A099757.name: Molien series for complete weight enumerators of Hermitian self-dual codes over the Galois ring GR(4,2).

A099759.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,0)=1, T(n,n)=1, T(n, k) = 2*(n-k)*T(n-1, k-1) + 2*k*T(n-1, k).

A099761.name: a(n) = ( n*(n+2) )^2.
formula: a(n) = (determinant [T(n-1) T(n) ; T(n+1) T(n+2)])^2 where T is A000217. - _J. M. Bergot_, May 17 2012 and _Bernard Schott_, Aug 06 2019

A099763.name: Next available number such that the last digit of n and the first digit of n+1 sum to 4.

A099766.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of unbordered binary words of length n and weight k, n >= 0, 0 <= k <= n.

A099767.name: Number of n-digit palindromes in base n.

A099768.name: Largest (or middle) entry in row n of A099766.

A099771.name: Smallest n-aspiring number. That is, a(n) = smallest k such that s^(n)(k) is perfect but s^(n-1)(k) is not, where s(k) is the sum of the aliquot parts of k and s^(i) means iterate s i times.

A099773.name: Number of partitions of n into odd prime parts.

A099774.name: Number of divisors of 2*n-1.
formula: Dirichlet g.f. (with interpolated zeros): zeta(s)^2*(1-1/2^s)^2. - _Geoffrey Critzer_, Feb 15 2015

A099775.name: Primes of the form pq - 6, where p and q are consecutive primes.

A099776.name: Length of the hypotenuse of an integer right triangle with the hypotenuse being one more than the longer side. The shorter sides are just consecutive odd numbers 3, 5, 7, ...
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + 4*n for n>1, a(1)=5. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Nov 17 2010
All other formulas given in A001844 also apply, with the restriction n>0. - _M. F. Hasler_, Nov 03 2012

A099777.name: Number of divisors of 2n.
formula: Moebius transform is period 2 sequence [2, 1, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 20 2005
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ n/2 * (3*log(n) + log(2) + 6*gamma - 3), where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 13 2019
a(n) = 4 iff n = 4 or n is an odd prime (A065091);
a(n) = 6 iff n = 16, or n = 2p for p an odd prime (A100484 \ {4}), or n = p^2 for p an odd prime (A001248 \ {4});

A099778.name: Number of perfect matchings in a certain class of graphs.

A099789.name: Records for terms in the continued fraction of Catalan's constant.

A099790.name: Positions of records for terms in the continued fraction of Catalan's constant.

A099791.name: Records for terms in the continued fraction of the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant A.

A099792.name: Positions of records for terms in the continued fraction of the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant A.

A099793.name: Table read by rows where row n consists of 2n terms representing k-matches described in A098813.

A099794.name: a(n) = smallest integer k such that k*prime(n) == 1 mod j for each integer j with 1<j<prime(n).

A099797.name: a(n) is taken to be the smallest positive integer greater than a(n-1) which is consistent with the condition "n is a member of the sequence if and only if a(n) is composite".

A099798.name: a(n) is taken to be the smallest positive integer greater than a(n-1) which is consistent with the condition "n is a member of the sequence if and only if a(n) is not composite".

A099799.name: a(n) = least integer that begins a run of exactly n consecutive integers that can be the hypotenuse of a Pythagorean triangle.

A099801.name: PrimePi(2n+1), the number of primes less than or equal to 2n+1.

A099802.name: Bisection of A000720.
formula: a(n) = A000720(n) + A035250(n) - A010051(n). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jul 05 2010

A099804.name: Records for terms in the continued fraction of Soldner's constant.

A099805.name: Positions of records for terms in the continued fraction of Soldner's constant (using indexing of first term as a(1) instead of a(0)).

A099806.name: If a,b are prime numbers satisfying the Diophantine equation a^3+b^3=c^2, then a is -1 mod 12 and b is 1 mod 12, or vice versa. Choose 'a' to be -1 mod 12. This is the sequence of 'a' values, sorted by the magnitude of c.

A099807.name: If a,b are prime numbers satisfying the Diophantine equation a^3+b^3=c^2, then a is -1 mod 12 and b is 1 mod 12, or vice versa. Choose 'b' to be 1 mod 12. This is the sequence of 'b' values, sorted by the magnitude of c.

A099808.name: If a,b are primes which satisfy the Diophantine equation a^3 + b^3 = c^2, then this sequence consists of the numbers sqrt((a+b)/48), sorted by the magnitude of c.

A099809.name: Let a,b be prime numbers satisfying the Diophantine equation a^3+b^3=(a+b)*(a^2-a*b+b^2)=c^2. Then the second factor a^2-a*b+b^2 is 3*e^2 for some integer e. This sequence tabulates the 'e' values, sorted by magnitude of c.

A099810.name: a(n) = a(n-1) XOR (a(n-1) + a(n-2)), with a(1)=1, a(2)=3, where XOR is the binary exclusive OR operation.

A099811.name: a(n) = a(n-1) XOR Sum_{k=1..n-1} a(k), with a(1)=1, a(2)=3, where XOR is the binary exclusive OR operation.

A099812.name: Number of distinct primes dividing 2n (i.e., omega(2n)).

A099814.name: Bisection of A002275.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + 11*100^(n-1) with a(0)=0. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Nov 16 2010

A099815.name: Maximum determinant that can be formed from the optimal set of nonnegative 3 X 3 matrix elements <=n, which maximize the number of different determinants given in A099834.

A099816.name: Bisection of A000796 (decimal expansion of Pi).

A099817.name: Bisection of A000796 (decimal expansion of Pi).

A099820.name: Even nonnegative integers in base 2 (bisection of A007088).

A099821.name: Odd positive integers in base 2 (bisection of A007088).

A099824.name: a(n) = Sum of the first 10^n primes.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=1..10^n} A000040(i). - _José de Jesús Camacho Medina_, Dec 27 2014 (corrected by _Joerg Arndt_, Jan 05 2015)

A099827.name: Generalized harmonic number H(n,5) = Sum_{k=1..n} 1/k^5 multiplied by (n!)^5.
formula: a(n) ~ Zeta(5) * (2*Pi)^(5/2) * n^(5*n+5/2) / exp(5*n). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Aug 27 2017
Sum_{n>=0} a(n) * x^n / (n!)^5 = polylog(5,x) / (1 - x). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 14 2020

A099828.name: Numerator of the generalized harmonic number H(n,5) = Sum_{k=1..n} 1/k^5.

A099829.name: Smallest perimeter S such that at least n distinct Pythagorean triangles with this perimeter can be constructed.

A099830.name: Smallest perimeter S such that exactly n distinct Pythagorean triangles with this perimeter can be constructed.

A099831.name: Perimeters of Pythagorean triangles that can be constructed in exactly 2 different ways.

A099832.name: Perimeters of Pythagorean triangles that can be constructed in exactly 3 different ways.

A099833.name: Perimeters of Pythagorean triangles that can be constructed in exactly 4 different ways.

A099834.name: Maximum number of different determinants that can be produced by permuting the elements of a 3 X 3 integer matrix with nonnegative entries <= n.

A099837.name: Expansion of (1 - x^2) / (1 + x + x^2) in powers of x.
formula: Euler transform of length 3 sequence [-1, -1, 1]. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 21 2011
Moebius transform is length 3 sequence [-1, 0, 3]. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 22 2011
a(n) = -b(n) where b(n) = A061347(n) is multiplicative with b(3^e) = -2 if e > 0, b(p^e) = 1 otherwise. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 19 2012
a(n) = a(-n). a(n) = c_3(n) if n > 1 where c_k(n) is Ramanujan's sum. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 21 2011
Dirichlet g.f.: Sum_{n>=1} a(n)/n^s = zeta(s)*(3^(1-s)-1). - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 11 2011
a(n+3) = R(n,-1) for n >= 0, with the monic Chebyshev T-polynomials R with coefficient table A127672. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Feb 27 2014
For n > 0, a(n) = 2*cos(n*Pi/3)*cos(n*Pi). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 25 2017

A099843.name: A transform of the Fibonacci numbers.

A099844.name: An Alexander sequence for the knot 8_2.

A099845.name: A Chebyshev transform of A090400 related to the knot 8_2.

A099846.name: An Alexander sequence for the knot 8_5.

A099848.name: All natural numbers occur in their order as many times as they have ordered prime factorizations.

A099850.name: Sum of the first n terms of A004648 (the remainder after dividing n-th prime by n).

A099851.name: Numbers n such that A099850(n) is divisible by n.

A099852.name: Terms in A099850 that are divisible by their position in that sequence.

A099853.name: Values of A099852 divided by the corresponding values in A099851. These are the integer results of dividing the terms of A099850 by their position in that sequence.

A099854.name: A Chebyshev transform of A048739 related to the knot 8_5.

A099855.name: a(n) = n*2^n - 2^(n/2)*sin(Pi*n/4).
formula: Related to binomial transform of A002265. Sequence is identical to its fourth differences (cf. A139756, A137221). See also A097064, A135035, A038504, A135356. - _Paul Curtz_, Jun 18 2008

A099859.name: A Chebyshev transform of A006053 related to the knot 7_1.

A099860.name: A Chebyshev transform related to the knot 7_1.

A099864.name: Indices of the primes used in A099863, which is a permutation of the odd primes that satisfies the condition that the sequence modulo 2^n has period 2^(n-1) for all n>0, where the least unused primes are chosen in the process.

A099865.name: Numerator of sum of all elements M(i,j,k) = i*j/k, (i,j,k = 1..n). a(n) = Numerator[Sum[Sum[Sum[i*j/k,{i,1,n}],{j,1,n}],{k,1,n}]].

A099866.name: Denominator of sum of all elements M(i,j,k) = i*j/k, (i,j,k = 1..n). a(n) = Denominator[Sum[Sum[Sum[i*j/k,{i,1,n}],{j,1,n}],{k,1,n}]].
formula: a(n) = denominator of ((n^2+n)/2)^2*Sum(1/i, i=1..n). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Oct 30 2004

formula: a(n) = binomial(2*n, n) * Sum_{k=0..n} k! * Stirling2(n, k).

A099882.name: Number of triples of n-node simple graphs that are isospectral (excluding quadruples, etc.).

A099883.name: Number of simple n-node graphs that are isospectral to at least one other graph on n nodes.

A099884.name: XOR difference triangle of the powers of 2, read by rows; Square array A(row,col): A(0,col) = 2^col, A(row,col) = A048724(A(row-1, col)) for row > 0, read by descending antidiagonals.
formula: T(n, k) = 2^(n-k)*A001317(k). T(n, n) = A001317(n) = SumXOR_{k=0..n} A047999(n, k)*2^k, where SumXOR is the analog of summation under the binary XOR operation.
When viewed as a square array A(row,col), with row >= 0, col >= 0, the following recurrences and formulas are valid:
A(0,col) = A000079(col), for row > 0, A(row,col) = A048724(A(row-1, col)).
With the definitions from _Antti Karttunen_ above, A(row+1, col) = A048720(3, A(row, col)). - _Peter Munn_, Jan 13 2020

A099885.name: Central terms of the rows of the XOR difference triangle of the powers of 2 (A099884) so that a(n) = A099884(n,[n/2]).
formula: a(n) = 2^[(n+1)/2]*A001317([n/2]), where A001317 forms the XOR BINOMIAL transform of the powers of 2.
It appears that a(2*n) = A117998(n). - _Peter Bala_, Feb 01 2017

A099886.name: XOR binomial transform of A099885.
formula: a(n) = SumXOR_{k=0..n} SumXOR_{i=0..k\2} (C(n, k)mod 2) * (C(k\2, i) mod 2) * 2^((k+1)\2+k\2-i), where the SumXOR is the analog of summation under XOR and x\y stands for floor(x/y) (see Pari program).

A099887.name: XOR difference triangle of the powers of 3, read by rows.
formula: T(n, k) = SumXOR_{i=0..k} (C(k, i)mod 2)*3^i, where SumXOR is the analog of summation under the binary XOR operation and C(k, i)mod 2 = A047999(k, i).

A099888.name: XOR BINOMIAL transform of the powers of 3.
formula: a(n) = SumXOR_{k=0..n} (C(n, k) mod 2)*3^k, where SumXOR is summation under XOR.

A099889.name: XOR difference triangle of the odd numbers, read by rows.
formula: T(n, k) = SumXOR_{i=0..k} (C(k, i)mod 2)*(2*(n-i)+1), where SumXOR is the analog of summation under the binary XOR operation and C(k, i)mod 2 = A047999(k, i). T(2^n, 2^n) = 2^(n+1) for n>=0, with T(0, 0)=1.

A099890.name: XOR BINOMIAL transform of the odd numbers; also the main diagonal of the XOR difference triangle A099889.

A099891.name: XOR difference triangle of A003188 (Gray code numbers), read by rows.
formula: T(n, k) = SumXOR_{i=0..k} (C(k, i)mod 2)*(A003188(n-i)), where SumXOR is the analog of summation under the binary XOR operation and C(k, i)mod 2 = A047999(k, i). T(2^n, 2^n) = 3*2^(n-1) for n>0, with T(1, 1)=1 and T(k, k)=0 elsewhere.
T(n,1) = A006519(n), the lowest 1-bit of n (see formula by Franklin T. Adams-Watters in A003188). - _Kevin Ryde_, Jul 02 2020

A099892.name: XOR BINOMIAL transform of A003188 (Gray code numbers); also the main diagonal of the XOR difference triangle A099891.
formula: a(2^n) = 3*2^(n-1) for n>0, with a(0)=0, a(1) = 1 and a(k)=0 otherwise. a(n) = SumXOR_{i=0..n} (C(n, i)mod 2)*A003188(n-i), where A003188(k)=bitxor(k, [k/2]) and SumXOR is summation under XOR.

A099893.name: XOR BINOMIAL transform of A006068 (inverse Gray code).
formula: a(2^n) = 2^(n+1)-1 for n>0, with a(0)=0 and a(k)=0 otherwise. a(n) = SumXOR_{i=0..n} (C(n, i)mod 2)*A006068(n-i) and SumXOR is summation under XOR.

A099894.name: XOR BINOMIAL transform of A038712.
formula: a(2^n-1) = 2^n for n>=0 and a(k)=0 otherwise. a(n) = SumXOR_{i=0..n} (C(n, i)mod 2)*A038712(n-i) and SumXOR is summation under XOR.

A099895.name: XOR BINOMIAL transform of A000069 (Odious numbers).
formula: a(2^n) = 2^(n+1)+1 for n>0, with a(0)=1 and a(k)=0 otherwise. a(n) = SumXOR_{i=0..n} (C(n, i)mod 2)*A000069(n-i) and SumXOR is summation under XOR.

A099896.name: A permutation of the natural numbers where a(n) = n XOR [n/2] XOR [n/4].
formula: XOR BINOMIAL transform begins: B={1, 2, 3, 7, 7, 0, 0, 14, 14, 0, 0, ...} and continues with B(2^k)=B(2^k+1)=7*2^(k-2) (for k>=2) and zeros elsewhere.

A099897.name: XOR difference triangle, read by rows, of A099898 (in leftmost column) such that the main diagonal equals A099898 shift left and divided by 4.
formula: T(n, [n/2]) = 4^n. T(n+1, 0) = 4*T(n, n) (n>=0); T(0, 0)=1; T(n, k) = T(n, k-1) XOR T(n-1, k-1) for n>k>0. T(n, k) = SumXOR_{i=0..k} (C(k, i)mod 2)*T(n-i, 0), where SumXOR is the analog of summation under the binary XOR operation and C(k, i)mod 2 = A047999(k, i).

A099898.name: Shifts left and divides by 4 under the XOR BINOMIAL transform (A099899).
formula: a(0)=1; a(n) = SumXOR_{k=0..n-1} (C(n-1-k+[k/2], [k/2])mod 2)*4^(k+1) for n>0. a(n) = SumXOR_{i=0..n} (C(n, i)mod 2)*A099899(n-i), where SumXOR is the analog of summation under the binary XOR operation and C(k, i)mod 2 = A047999(k, i).

A099899.name: Multiplies by 4 and shifts right under the XOR BINOMIAL transform (A099898).
formula: a(n) = SumXOR_{k=0..n} (C(n-k+[k/2], [k/2])mod 2)*2^k for n>=0. a(n) = SumXOR_{i=0..n} (C(n, i)mod 2)*A099898(n-i), where SumXOR is the analog of summation under the binary XOR operation and C(i, j)mod 2 = A047999(i, j).

A099900.name: XOR difference triangle, read by rows, of A099901 (in leftmost column) such that the main diagonal equals A099901 shift left and divided by 2.
formula: T(n, [n/2]) = 2^n. T(n+1, 0) = 2*T(n, n) (n>=0); T(0, 0)=1; T(n, k) = T(n, k-1) XOR T(n-1, k-1) for n>k>0. T(n, k) = SumXOR_{i=0..k} (C(k, i)mod 2)*T(n-i, 0), where SumXOR is the analog of summation under the binary XOR operation and C(k, i)mod 2 = A047999(k, i).

A099901.name: Shifts left and divides by 2 under the XOR BINOMIAL transform (A099902).
formula: a(0)=1; a(n) = SumXOR_{k=0..n-1} (C(n-1-k+[k/2], [k/2])mod 2)*2^(k+1) for n>0. a(n) = SumXOR_{i=0..n} (C(n, i)mod 2)*A099902(n-i), where SumXOR is the analog of summation under the binary XOR operation and C(k, i)mod 2 = A047999(k, i).

A099902.name: Multiplies by 2 and shifts right under the XOR BINOMIAL transform (A099901).
formula: a(n) = SumXOR_{k=0..n} (binomial(n-k+floor(k/2), floor(k/2)) mod 2)*2^k for n >= 0.
a(n) = SumXOR_{i=0..n} (C(n, i) mod 2)*A099901(n-i), where SumXOR is the analog of summation under the binary XOR operation and C(i, j) mod 2 = A047999(i, j).

A099903.name: Sum of all matrix elements of n X n matrix M(i,j) = i^3+j^3, (i,j = 1..n). a(n) = n^3*(n+1)^2/2.
formula: a(n) = (n^5 + 2*n^4 + n^3)/2. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Oct 27 2011

A099904.name: Numerator of sum of all matrix elements of N X N matrix M(i,j) = i^3+j^3, (i,j = 1..n) divided by n!.
formula: a(n) = Numerator[1/n!*Sum[Sum[(i^3+j^3), {i, 1, n}], {j, 1, n}]] a(n) = Numerator[1/2 * (n^3)*(n+1)^2 /n! ].

A099911.name: Primes of the form (p*(q-1) + (p-1)*q)/2, where p and q are consecutive odd primes.

A099912.name: Number of closed walks on the Herschel graph.

A099918.name: A Chebyshev transform related to the 7th cyclotomic polynomial.

A099919.name: F(3) + F(6) + F(9) + ... + F(3n), F(n) = Fibonacci numbers A000045.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{0 <= j <= i <= n} binomial(i, j)*F(i + j). - _Benoit Cloitre_, May 21 2005

A099920.name: a(n) = (n+1)*F(n), F(n) = Fibonacci numbers A000045.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2) + A000032(n-1) (Lucas numbers). - _Bob Selcoe_, Aug 19 2015

A099921.name: a(n) = 5*Fibonacci(n)^2.
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 2*a(n-2) - a(n-3) for n > 3. - _Matthew House_, Jan 13 2017

A099922.name: a(n) = F(4n) - 2n, where F(n) = Fibonacci numbers A000045.
formula: G.f.: x*(1+8*x+x^2)/((1-x)^2 * (1-7*x+x^2)). [Corrected for offset by _Georg Fischer_, May 24 2019]

A099923.name: Fourth powers of Lucas numbers A000032.

A099927.name: Pellonomial triangle P(k,n) read by rows.
formula: P(k, n) = Prod[i=k-n+1..k, Pell(i)] / Prod[i=1..n, Pell(i)], with Pell(n) = A000129(n).
In terms of the Pell numbers, Pell(n) = A000129(n), the triangle entry T(n,k) = [n]!/([k]!*[n-k]!), where [n]! := Pell(1)*...*Pell(n) for n >= 1, with the convention [0]! = 1.
Define E(x) = 1 + sum {n>=0} x^n/[n]!. Then a generating function for this triangle is E(z)*E(x*z) = 1 + (1 + x)*z + (1 + 2*x + x^2)*z^2/[2]! + (1 + 5*x + 5*x^2 + x^3)*z^3/[3]! + ... (End)

A099928.name: Row sums of Pellonomial triangle A099927.

A099930.name: a(n) = Pell(n)*Pell(n-1)*Pell(n-2) / 10.
formula: The following remarks assume an offset of 0.

The o.g.f. A(x) = 1/( (1 + 2*x - x^2)*(1 - 14*x - x^2) ). Hence A(x) (mod 4) = 1/(1 + 2*x - x^2)^2 (mod 4). It follows by Theorem 1 of Heninger et al. that sqrt(A(x)) = 1 + 6*x + 69*x^2 + 804*x^3 + ... has integral coefficients.
Sum_{n >= 0} a(n)*x^n = exp( Sum_{n >= 1} Pell(4*n)/Pell(n)*x^n/n ). Cf. A001656, A084175. (End)

A099932.name: Triangle read by rows: nonzero coefficients of polynomials 2^n*E(n,x), with E the Euler polynomials.

A099936.name: Primes of the form 1 + product of first n prime gaps.

A099937.name: Primes not of the form floor(k + (1/2)*log(k)^2).

A099938.name: Consider the sequence of circles C0, C1, C2, C3 ..., where C0 is a half-circle of radius 1. C1 is the largest circle that fits into C0 and has radius 1/2. C(n+1) is the largest circle that fits inside C0 but outside C(n), etc. Sequence gives the curvatures (reciprocals of the radii) of the circles.

A099939.name: Seven-segment LED clock sequence: starting at 00:00 midnight, sequence gives total number of illuminated segments every minute that appear in the hour and minute characters of the LED display on a digital clock.

A099940.name: a(n) = 2*(A056855(n)) /(phi(n)*n), where phi() is the Euler phi function.

A099942.name: Start with 1, then alternately double or add 2.

A099943.name: Number of 5 X n binary matrices avoiding simultaneously the right angled numbered polyomino patterns (ranpp) (00;1), (01,1) and (11;0).

A099944.name: Number of 3 X n binary matrices avoiding simultaneously the right angled numbered polyomino patterns (ranpp) (00;1) and (11;0).

A099945.name: Number of 4 X n binary matrices avoiding simultaneously the right angled numbered polyomino patterns (ranpp) (00;1) and (11;0).

A099947.name: Number of topologically connected set partitions of {1,...,n}.
formula: (1) A(x) = Sum_{n>=0} A000110(n)*x^n/A(x)^n, where A000110 are the Bell numbers.

B(n) = Sum_p Product_{s in p} a(|s|) where p is a non-crossing set partition of {1,...,n} and B = A000110. In words, every set partition of {1,...,n} can be uniquely decomposed as a non-crossing set partition together with a topologically connected set partition of each block. - _Gus Wiseman_, Feb 19 2019

A099948.name: Number of partitions of n such that the number of blocks is congruent to 3 mod 4.

A099949.name: Number of crossing partitions of n.

A099950.name: Number of 2-sparse nonoverlapping partitions of n.

A099951.name: Length of shortest maximal Abelian squarefree word over alphabet of size n.

A099952.name: Number of Wilf classes in S_n.

A099953.name: a(n) = A076795(n) - 1.
formula: a(n) = (2*n-2)*a(n-1)-(2*n-3)*a(n-2) with a(1)=0, a(2)=1. - _Emeric Deutsch_ and _Ira M. Gessel_, Dec 19 2004
G.f.: A(x)=x/(1-x)/(U(0)-x), where U(k)= (2*k+1)*x + 1 - (2*k+3)*x/U(k+1); (continued fraction Euler's 1st kind, 1-step ). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 27 2012

A099954.name: Numbers n such that Fibonacci(n) is a semiprime and its reversal is a different semiprime.

A099955.name: Atomic numbers in first column in the Mendeleyev periodic table of elements.

A099956.name: Atomic numbers of the alkaline earth metals.

A099958.name: (1/2)*number of distinct angular positions under which an observer positioned at the center of an edge of a square lattice can see the (2n)X(2n-1) points symmetrically surrounding his position.
formula: This is a bisection of A049690, that is, a(n) = Sum[k=1..2n+1, phi(2k)]. - _Ralf Stephan_, Nov 13, 2004.

A099959.name: Triangle read by rows: Each row is constructed by forming the partial sums of the previous row, reading from the right and at every other row repeating the final term.

A099960.name: An interleaving of the Genocchi numbers of the first and second kind, A110501 and A005439.

A099961.name: Triangle read by rows: Each row is constructed by forming the partial sums of the previous row, reading from the right and at every third row repeating the final term.

A099962.name: First column (also row sums) of triangle in A099961.

A099963.name: Sequence of the next-to-last entries in the rows of A099961.

A099964.name: Triangle read by rows: The n-th row is constructed by forming the partial sums of the previous row, reading from the right and if n is a triangular number repeating the final term.

A099965.name: First column (also row sums) of triangle in A099964.

A099966.name: Sequence of the next-to-last entries in the rows of A099964.

A099967.name: Second column of triangle in A099961.

A099968.name: Second column of triangle in A099964.

A099969.name: Write 1/e as a binary fraction; read this from left to right and whenever a 1 appears, note the integer formed by reading leftwards from that 1.

A099970.name: Write 1/e as a binary fraction; read this from left to right and whenever a 1 appears, note the integer formed by reading leftwards from that 1. Then convert those integers from binary into decimal numbers.

A099971.name: Write (sqrt(5)-1)/2 as a binary fraction; read this from left to right and whenever a 1 appears, note the integer formed by reading leftwards from that 1.

A099972.name: Write 1/sqrt(2) as a binary fraction; read this from left to right and whenever a 1 appears, note the integer formed by reading leftwards from that 1.

A099973.name: Write Euler's constant gamma as a binary fraction; read this from left to right and whenever a 1 appears, note the integer formed by reading leftwards from that 1.

A099974.name: Write log(2) as a binary fraction; read this from left to right and whenever a 1 appears, note the integer formed by reading leftwards from that 1.

A099975.name: Bisection of A014137.
formula: a(n) = sum(binomial(2k, k)/(k+1), k=0..2n+1). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Dec 20 2004

A099976.name: Bisection of A000984.
formula: G.f.: 2*sqrt(2)/sqrt(1-16*x)/sqrt(1+sqrt(1-16*x)) = 2 + 60*x/(G(0)-30*x) where G(k)= 2*x*(4*k+3)*(4*k+5) + (2*k+3)*(k+1)- 2*x*(k+1)*(2*k+3)*(4*k+7)*(4*k+9)/G(k+1); (continued fraction, Euler's 1st kind, 1-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 14 2012

A099977.name: Bisection of Bell numbers, A000110.
formula: a(n) = exp(-1) * Sum_{k>=0} k^(2*n+1)/k!. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jun 13 2019

A099991.name: a(n) = Moebius(2n).
formula: a(n) = mu(2n) = A008683(2n). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Dec 17 2013

A099999.name: Number of geometrical configurations of type (n_3).

A100000.name: Middle column of marks found on the oldest object with logical carvings, the 22000-year-old Ishango bone from the Congo.
